Context:

Amazon is one of the biggest hubs of online shopping of the modern day, and has not only shaped how people shop, but also how they sell. Boasting over 9.7 million registered vendors worldwide, many use amazon.com to make a living. Using Predictive Modeling, vendors can now use available data (such as the data provided in this Amazon Sales Dataset) to predict how many sales their product is estimated to get based on its features.

What This Notebook Looks To Answer:

What features of a product will influence higher ratings or reviews for a product? Does the rating or price of a product determine how many sales (assuming rating_count is only made up of customers who bought the product) a product will receive?

Limitations Of This Dataset:

The data in the Amazon Sales Dataset (linked below) was scraped from the official Amazon website. This Dataset does not include any actual sales data, which limit how accurately the predictive model can predict sales based on the features provided. All analysis and conclusions are made assuming all reviews were made by customers who bought the products listed. All price categories are also provided in Indian Rupee, which may affect the conclusion. Despite this, all efforts were made to convert data types and prices into something workable.

Link to Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/karkavelrajaj/amazon-sales-dataset/data

Observations

The Dataset Itself:

The Amazon Sales Dataset has 16 features and 1,465 entries. Of the features listed, these are of interest: product_name, category, discounted_price, actual_price, discount_percentage, rating, and rating_count.

Missing Data:

The dataset is mostly complete with only 2 entries missing for rating_count.

Data Types:

All features of interest are of the object data type, which will not work well for visualisation and predictive modeling. The data will need to be converted into numeric types so that we can begin working with it.

Additional Notes:

Some entries in the dataset are repeated.

Convert Data Type to Float And Prices To USD

The original dataset provides our data as objects, so we need to convert our data to float. In addition, the price categories are provided in Indian Rupee, so it needs to be converted into USD.

In[44]:
# Function to clean and convert currency columns
def clean_currency(price_str):
    if isinstance(price_str, str):
        return float(price_str.replace('', '').replace(',', ''))
    return float(price_str)

# Apply the cleaning function to price columns
data_clean['discounted_price'] = data_clean['discounted_price'].apply(clean_currency)
data_clean['actual_price'] = data_clean['actual_price'].apply(clean_currency)

# Convert discount_percentage to float
data_clean['discount_percentage'] = data_clean['discount_percentage'].str.replace('%', '').astype(float)

# Convert rating and rating_count to float, handling potential errors
data_clean['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(data_clean['rating'], errors='coerce')
data_clean['rating_count'] = data_clean['rating_count'].str.replace(',', '').astype(float)

# Drop rows with missing rating values
data_clean.dropna(subset=['rating'], inplace=True)


print("Data types after conversion:")
print(data_clean.info())
print("\nSample of cleaned data:")
display(data_clean.head())

Data Analysis Summary:

  • Products across a wide range of prices have varied ratings. The box plot for rating by main_category suggests that the distribution of ratings is relatively consistent across most categories, although there might be subtle differences in the median or spread.
  • Product ratings are concentrated around higher values, indicating a skew towards positive reviews.
  • The distribution of rating counts is highly skewed, with a majority of products having very few ratings and a few products having a very high amount of ratings.
  • The correlation matrix shows a strong positive correlation between discounted_price_usd and actual_price_usd. As the actual price of a product increases, its discounted price also tends to increase.
  • There is a moderate negative correlation between actual_price_usd and discount_percentage, and a moderate negative correlation between discounted_price_usd and discount_percentage.
  • Most entries for discount_percentage vary, but most seem to be around 40%-60%.

Train And Evaluate Our Models

In[57]:
# Initialize a DataFrame to store results
results_df_transformed = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Feature Set', 'Num Features', 'Train RMSE', 'Val RMSE', 'Train R', 'Val R', 'Generalization Gap'])

# Train and evaluate Linear Regression model
for name, features in feature_sets_transformed.items():
    # Select the features for the current set
    X_train_fs_transformed = X_train_transformed[features]
    X_val_fs_transformed = X_val_transformed[features]

    # Initialize and train the Linear Regression model
    model_transformed = LinearRegression()

    # Scale the features
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_fs_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train_fs_transformed)
    X_val_fs_scaled = scaler.transform(X_val_fs_transformed)

    model_transformed.fit(X_train_fs_scaled, y_train_transformed)

    # Predict on training and validation sets
    y_train_pred_transformed = model_transformed.predict(X_train_fs_scaled)
    y_val_pred_transformed = model_transformed.predict(X_val_fs_scaled)

    # Calculate RMSE and R for training and validation sets
    train_rmse_transformed = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train_transformed, y_train_pred_transformed))
    val_rmse_transformed = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val_transformed, y_val_pred_transformed))
    train_r2_transformed = r2_score(y_train_transformed, y_train_pred_transformed)
    val_r2_transformed = r2_score(y_val_transformed, y_val_pred_transformed)

    # Calculate generalization gap
    generalization_gap_transformed = train_rmse_transformed - val_rmse_transformed

    # Store the results
    results_df_transformed = pd.concat([results_df_transformed, pd.DataFrame({
        'Feature Set': [name],
        'Num Features': [len(features)],
        'Train RMSE': [train_rmse_transformed],
        'Val RMSE': [val_rmse_transformed],
        'Train R': [train_r2_transformed],
        'Val R': [val_r2_transformed],
        'Generalization Gap': [generalization_gap_transformed]
    })], ignore_index=True)

# Display the results
display(results_df_transformed)

FINAL Performance Estimation On Test Set

In[61]:
# Get the selected feature set
selected_features = feature_sets_transformed[best_model]

# Combine train and validation data for final training
X_train_final = pd.concat([X_train_transformed[selected_features], X_val_transformed[selected_features]], ignore_index=True)
y_train_final = pd.concat([y_train_transformed, y_val_transformed], ignore_index=True)

# Get test set
X_test_final = X_test_transformed[selected_features]
y_test_final = y_test_transformed

# Train final model on combined train+val set
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

final_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('model', LinearRegression())
])

final_pipeline.fit(X_train_final, y_train_final)

# Evaluate on train set
y_train_pred = final_pipeline.predict(X_train_final)
train_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train_final, y_train_pred))
train_r2 = r2_score(y_train_final, y_train_pred)

# Evaluate on test set
y_test_pred = final_pipeline.predict(X_test_final)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_final, y_test_pred))
test_r2 = r2_score(y_test_final, y_test_pred)

print(f"\nFinal Performance Estimation (Test Set):")
print(f"Model: {best_model}")
print(f"Train RMSE: {train_rmse:.4f}")
print(f"Train R: {train_r2:.4f}")
print(f"Test RMSE: {test_rmse:.4f}")
print(f"Test R: {test_r2:.4f}")
print(f"Generalization Gap: {test_rmse - train_rmse:.4f}")

Part 5 - Conclusion

While there isn't a strong linear relationship between price and rating, product ratings tend to be high overall, with a skewed distribution towards positive reviews. The distribution of rating counts is also very skewed, indicating that most products have few reviews, while a small number have many. The correlation analysis revealed a strong positive relationship between discounted and actual prices, and a moderate negative relationship between price and discount percentage.

For the predictive modeling for rating_count (assuming everyone who reviewed the product bought it), the LinearRegression model with the 'All Original' feature set performed the best on the validation set, achieving the lowest RMSE out of all the feature sets. The final evaluation on the test set showed a similar performance.

While the model gives an estimate for rating_count, the R value suggests that the selected features only explain a portion of the variance in rating_count. This means that other factors not included in this dataset likely influence the number of ratings a product receives. For the scope of this project, however, I feel that the features selected and analyzed are approprate.
